You can never contribute more to your IRA than you earned in that tax year. And, as previously mentioned, you receive no tax deduction for the contribution—although <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="1" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/articles/retirement/04/031704.asp">you may be able to take a Saver's Tax Credit</a> of 10%, 20%, or 50% of the deposit, depending on your income and life situation.<span class="ql-inline-citation" data-cite="6"></span>

Anyone who has taxable income can contribute to a Roth IRA—as long as they meet certain requirements concerning <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="1" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/f/filingstatus.asp" rel="noopener noreferrer">filing status</a> and <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="2" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/m/magi.asp" rel="noopener noreferrer">modified adjusted gross income</a> (MAGI). Those whose annual income is above a certain amount, which the IRS adjusts periodically, become ineligible to contribute.<span class="ql-inline-citation" data-cite="3">﻿</span>﻿ The chart below shows the figures for 2020 and 2021.<span class="ql-inline-citation" data-cite="18">﻿</span>﻿

